-- PRESS DIGEST - Bulgaria - Oct 15
-- 
-- Wed Oct 15, 2014 02:54AM EDT
-- None



SOFIA, Oct 15 (Reuters) - These are some of the main stories in Bulgarian newspapers on Friday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

-- Centre-right GERB party, which won the parliamentary elections earlier this month, declined ethnic Turkish Movement for Rights and Freedoms (DPS) offer of support for minority government (Capital daily, Standart, 24 Chasa, Presa, Trud, Sega, Monitor, Duma). -- Bulgarian President Rosen Plevneliev will meet leaders of political parties to agree on a date to convene the new parliament after the snap election. Sources, familiar with the issue, say Oct 22 or Oct 29 are most likely to be chosen (Presa, Standart, Monitor, Duma). -- Angry customers of troubled Corporate Commercial Bank (Corpbank) <6C9.BB> stormed the bank's headquarters, demanding to meet the lender's supervisory board. Depositors, who held a number of rallies in recent weeks, have vowed not to give up demonstrations until their calls are heeded. They insist Corpbank should be opened to allow customers the opportunity to use their money and demand to meet the supervisors to pose their questions (Presa, Sega, Trud, Standart, 24 Chasa, Duma). -- Bulgarian Prosecutor's Office has initiated a pre-court proceeding against troubled Corporate Commercial Bank (Corpbank)'s majority owner Tsvetan Vassilev and his wife Antoaneta Vassileva over money laundering (Presa, 24 Chasa, Monitor, Standart, Duma). -- Interim Justice Minister Hristo Ivanov demanded an independent international expert appraisal of the state of Bulgaria's prosecuting authority (Capital daily, 24 Chasa, Presa, Standart, Sega, Duma). -- Bulgarian capital Sofia has been named the 2018 European Capital of Sport 2018, the European Capitals and Cities of Sport Federation (ASEC Europe) said. In a letter to Sofia mayor Yordanka Fandakova, ACES Europe president Gian Francesco Lupatelli said that the city was a good example of the development of sport as a means to promote healthy living, integration and education, which were among the main objectives of the initiative (Capital daily, Standart, 24 Chasa, Duma).